  "text": "Lake Ohau (44814.040 0 S, 169851.240 0 E; 520 m above sea level) is one of three north-south trending lakes formed during the rapid glacial retreat between 17 900 and 17 4000 years ago following the last glacial maximum on the South Island of New Zealand (Fig. 1b) [CITATION_1] Two thermistor chains were arranged in depths of 25 m and 50 m near the head of the lake (Sites 1 and 2) and one thermistor chain near the outflow in the south-east (Site 3). Two ADCPs were located next to the moorings near the inflow at similar depths of 25 m and 50 m (Sites 1 and 2). LISST profiles were taken along the lake axis as shown in (a).",
